In HTTP Request Smuggling, one request is interpreted as two different requests because the front-end server and back-end server process headers differently


                                                                                  Main Impacts

Authentication Bypass
Attackers may bypass login protection and access restricted pages like /admin.

Session Hijacking
Attackers can capture or interfere with another user’s session request.

Cache Poisoning
Attackers can poison server caches so that other users receive malicious or incorrect responses.

Access to Sensitive Data
Hidden requests can retrieve private data or internal endpoints.

Web Application Firewall (WAF) Bypass
Security filters in the front-end proxy can be bypassed.

Account Takeover (ATO)
In some cases attackers can manipulate requests to take control of user accounts.

Internal Endpoint Access
Attackers may access internal APIs that should not be exposed.


